"23a_scaleddecimal.mst — ScaledDecimal: Squeak/Pharo's exact decimal number
 with a display scale, backing the `3.14s2` literal syntax (the lexer/parser
 desugar such a literal to `ScaledDecimal numerator:denominator:scale:`, the
 same build-at-runtime treatment brace arrays get). As in Squeak, this is a
 Fraction SUBCLASS: the value is an exact rational — arithmetic never loses
 precision — and `scale` only governs how many decimal places printing shows
 (rounded for display, exact underneath). Being a Fraction, every existing
 Fraction/Integer arithmetic path accepts one as an argument unchanged; the
 overrides below make results STAY scaled when the receiver is scaled, with
 the larger scale winning when both sides carry one.

 Two deliberate divergences from Squeak, both small: a plain `Integer op
 ScaledDecimal` answers an unscaled rational (Squeak's generality tower
 re-scales it; this world's simpler type-test dispatch puts the receiver in
 charge), and equal-value ScaledDecimal/Integer pairs can hash differently
 (same pre-existing property Fraction has vs Double)."

nil subclass: Object [
    isScaledDecimal [
        ^false
    ]
]

"Integer as a rational: numerator/denominator/asFraction let one Integer
 flow through every rational-arithmetic path (Fraction's and
 ScaledDecimal's) without a special case — Squeak defines exactly these."
Number subclass: Integer [
    numerator [ ^self ]
    denominator [ ^1 ]
    asFraction [ ^self ]
]

Number subclass: Fraction [
    asFraction [ ^self ]
]

"I am an exact decimal number: a Fraction that remembers how many decimal
 places to show. Write me as a literal — 3.14s2, 0.05s2, 100s2, 2.5s (scale
 from the fraction digits) — or build me with numerator:denominator:scale:
 or aNumber asScaledDecimal: places. My value is exact rational arithmetic
 (1s0 / 3s0 is exactly one third); scale only rounds what printing shows,
 so (1s0 / 3s0) printString is '0s0' but the value stays 1/3. Arithmetic
 with Integers, Fractions and other ScaledDecimals answers a ScaledDecimal
 carrying the larger scale; mixing with a Double answers a Double."
Fraction subclass: ScaledDecimal [
    | scale |

    "Reduce like Fraction but NEVER collapse to a plain Integer — 2.00s2
     must stay a ScaledDecimal (denominator 1 is legal here, unlike in
     Fraction proper, whose factory answers the Integer instead)."
    ScaledDecimal class >> numerator: n denominator: d scale: s [
        | g num den sign |
        d = 0 ifTrue: [ ^self error: 'division by zero' ].
        sign := d < 0 ifTrue: [ -1 ] ifFalse: [ 1 ].
        num := n * sign.
        den := d * sign.
        g := num gcd: den.
        g = 0 ifTrue: [ g := 1 ].
        ^(self basicNew setNumerator: num // g denominator: den // g) setScale: s
    ]
    "Wrap any exact rational (Integer, Fraction, or ScaledDecimal)."
    ScaledDecimal class >> fromRational: r scale: s [
        ^self numerator: r numerator denominator: r denominator scale: s
    ]

    setScale: s [ scale := s. ^self ]
    scale [ ^scale ]
    isScaledDecimal [ ^true ]

    "The plain (unscaled) exact value — a Fraction, or an Integer when the
     denominator is 1 (Fraction's factory collapses it)."
    asFraction [
        ^Fraction numerator: self numerator denominator: self denominator
    ]

    "The result scale: mine, or the larger of the two when the other side
     is scaled too — Squeak's rule."
    scaleWith: aNumber [
        ^aNumber isScaledDecimal
            ifTrue: [ scale max: aNumber scale ]
            ifFalse: [ scale ]
    ]

    "── arithmetic: exact underneath, scaled on top; Double converts ──
     The exact work is delegated to Fraction's own operations on the
     unscaled values (which handle Integer/Fraction/ScaledDecimal
     arguments uniformly — a ScaledDecimal IS a Fraction), then the
     result is re-wrapped at the combined scale."
    + aNumber [
        aNumber isDouble ifTrue: [ ^self asDouble + aNumber ].
        ^ScaledDecimal fromRational: self asFraction + aNumber
            scale: (self scaleWith: aNumber)
    ]
    - aNumber [
        aNumber isDouble ifTrue: [ ^self asDouble - aNumber ].
        ^ScaledDecimal fromRational: self asFraction - aNumber
            scale: (self scaleWith: aNumber)
    ]
    * aNumber [
        aNumber isDouble ifTrue: [ ^self asDouble * aNumber ].
        ^ScaledDecimal fromRational: self asFraction * aNumber
            scale: (self scaleWith: aNumber)
    ]
    / aNumber [
        aNumber isDouble ifTrue: [ ^self asDouble / aNumber ].
        ^ScaledDecimal fromRational: self asFraction / aNumber
            scale: (self scaleWith: aNumber)
    ]
    negated [
        ^ScaledDecimal numerator: self numerator negated
            denominator: self denominator scale: scale
    ]
    abs [
        ^self negative ifTrue: [ self negated ] ifFalse: [ self ]
    ]
    reciprocal [
        ^ScaledDecimal numerator: self denominator
            denominator: self numerator scale: scale
    ]

    "Equality is by VALUE across the whole exact tower: 2.00s2 = 2 and
     3.14s2 = 157/50 are both true (the inherited Fraction = would answer
     false against an Integer, because a proper Fraction is never whole).
     Comparison (<, <= ...) needs no override — Fraction's cross-multiply
     is value-exact for a denominator of 1 too."
    = aNumber [
        aNumber isDouble ifTrue: [ ^self asDouble = aNumber ].
        aNumber isScaledDecimal ifTrue: [ ^self asFraction = aNumber asFraction ].
        ^self asFraction = aNumber
    ]
    hash [
        ^self asFraction hash
    ]

    "Print rounded to `scale` decimal places, then the s-suffix — the
     literal syntax back again: 3.14s2, -0.50s2, 100s0. The value itself
     stays exact; only the digits shown are rounded."
    printOn: aStream [
        | den scaled intPart fracPart digits |
        self negative ifTrue: [ aStream nextPutAll: '-' ].
        den := 10 raisedTo: scale.
        scaled := self asFraction abs * den.
        scaled := scaled isFraction ifTrue: [ scaled rounded ] ifFalse: [ scaled ].
        intPart := scaled // den.
        fracPart := scaled \\ den.
        intPart printOn: aStream.
        scale > 0 ifTrue: [
            aStream nextPutAll: '.'.
            digits := fracPart printString.
            (scale - digits size) timesRepeat: [ aStream nextPutAll: '0' ].
            aStream nextPutAll: digits ].
        aStream nextPutAll: 's'.
        scale printOn: aStream.
    ]
]

"Convert any exact number to a scaled decimal: 17 asScaledDecimal: 2
 prints '17.00s2'; (1/3) asScaledDecimal: 4 prints '0.3333s4'. Defined for
 the exact tower only — a Double's bits are not a decimal the user wrote,
 so guessing a rational for one is a trap Squeak also declines."
Number subclass: Integer [
    asScaledDecimal: s [ ^ScaledDecimal fromRational: self scale: s ]
]
Number subclass: Fraction [
    asScaledDecimal: s [ ^ScaledDecimal fromRational: self scale: s ]
]
